  "texts": [
    "Let us analyze both directions of this equivalence.First, since φ is to be a consequence of ¬¬φ, any classical partial-state model is such that if M, x ⊩ ¬¬φ, then M, x ⊩ φ, or equivalently, if M, x ⊮ φ, then M, x ⊮ ¬¬φ, which is equivalent to:• Refinability -if M, x ⊮ φ, then ∃x ′ ⊑ x: M, x ′ ⊩ ¬φ.Note that if M, x ⊮ ¬φ, then ∃x ′ ⊑ x: M, x ′ ⊩ φ, by the semantics of ¬.",
    "So the idea behind Refinability is this: if φ is indeterminate at x, i.e., if M, x ⊮ φ and M, x ⊮ ¬φ, then there is a refinement of x that decides φ negatively and a refinement of x that decides φ affirmatively.",
    "This gives us the classical view of possibilities: indeterminacy with respect to φ is equivalent to having refinements that determine φ each way.Second, since ¬¬φ is to be a consequence of φ, any classical partial-state model is such that if M, x ⊩ φ, then M, x ⊩ ¬¬φ.",
    "Given Refinability, this condition is equivalent to the condition from Example 2.7:• Persistence: if M, x ⊩ φ and x ′ ⊑ x, then M, x ′ ⊩ φ.For if M, x ⊩ φ but M, x ′ ⊮ φ, then by Refinability there is an x ′′ ⊑ x ′ such that M, x ′′ ⊩ ¬φ, which with x ′′ ⊑ x from the transitivity of ⊑ implies M, x ⊮ ¬¬φ.",
    "So for ¬¬φ to be a consequence of φ, Persistence is necessary."
  ],
